{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14677"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14677"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.57,0.08,0.11,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90592"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7370"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"628"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"3617"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44215"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90592"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent after developing a rash and facial swelling 30 minutes after eating scrambled eggs for breakfast. This is his first known exposure to egg. The symptoms have since resolved with antihistamine treatment at home, and he is now well. He has a history of moderate eczema but no other medical conditions. He does not take any regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is no residual urticaria or periorbital swelling. His chest is clear on auscultation with no wheeze. There is no stridor or tongue swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Total serum IgE level","Referral for skin prick testing in 2-4 weeks","Complete blood count with eosinophils","Patch testing","Oral food challenge"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with an IgE-mediated food allergy to egg, manifesting with acute onset urticaria and angioedema following first known exposure. The timing and nature of symptoms are typical of an immediate-type hypersensitivity reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for skin prick testing\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred initial investigation for suspected IgE-mediated food allergy, but it should be delayed for at least 2 weeks after an acute allergic reaction. During an acute reaction, skin reactivity may be temporarily reduced due to mediator depletion, leading to false negative results. Additionally, antihistamines (which may be used to treat the acute reaction) can interfere with testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal serum IgE\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-specific test that may be elevated in various conditions including allergic disease, parasitic infections, and eczema. It does not provide information about specific allergen sensitisation and is therefore not helpful in diagnosing specific food allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral food challenge\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosis but is not appropriate as the initial investigation when there is a clear history of immediate reaction. It should be reserved for cases where there is diagnostic uncertainty or to assess if a child has outgrown their allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatch testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to investigate delayed hypersensitivity reactions such as contact dermatitis. It is not useful for diagnosing immediate-type food allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete blood count with eosinophils\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in allergic conditions but is non-specific and does not assist in diagnosing specific food allergies. It may be useful in monitoring other allergic conditions such as eosinophilic oesophagitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing confirmation of egg allergy, management would include education about strict avoidance, provision of an action plan, and prescription of an adrenaline auto-injector if indicated based on risk assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Immediate-onset food allergies typically present within minutes to 2 hours of exposure with urticaria, angioedema, or respiratory symptoms.","Skin prick testing should be delayed until at least 2 weeks after an acute allergic reaction to avoid false negative results.","Oral food challenges should be conducted in a supervised medical setting when diagnostic uncertainty exists."],"references":["Food Allergy in Children and Young People: Diagnosis and Assessment of Food Allergy in Children and Young People in Primary Care and Community Settings. London: National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence (NICE); 2011 Feb. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 116.) Appendix 1.0, Scope. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK82173/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":